OL,3,CWarm days, cold nights: What is behind
OL,4,Cthis week's big temperature gap?
OL,6,FHigh teens by day and frosty by night?
OL,8,FThe diurnal range can be at its
OL,9,Flargest at this time of year - but
OL,10,Fwhat actually is it and what does it
OL,11,Fmean for me this week?
OL,13,FWhat is the diurnal range?
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G1/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,309,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30802
SC,0002
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F308A1776769395
OL,3,CWarm days, cold nights: What is behind
OL,4,Cthis week's big temperature gap?
OL,6,FLike so many things in life, it sounds
OL,7,Ffancy and complicated, but it's
OL,8,Factually very simple. The diurnal
OL,9,Frange - or the diurnal temperature
OL,10,Frange (DTR) to give it its full name -
OL,11,Fis simply the name given to the
OL,12,Ftemperature difference between day and
OL,13,Fnight in a 24-hour period. For
OL,14,Fexample, if temperatures dropped to
OL,15,F-1C overnight and then rose to 20C the
OL,16,Fnext day, that would give a diurnal
OL,17,Frange of 21 degrees.
OL,19,FWhy does the range vary so much
OL,20,Fthroughout the year?
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G2/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,309,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30803
SC,0003
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F308A1776769395
OL,3,CWarm days, cold nights: What is behind
OL,4,Cthis week's big temperature gap?
OL,6,FThe diurnal range is influenced by
OL,7,Fanother complicated-sounding
OL,8,Fphenomenon called "thermal inertia",
OL,9,Fwhich, simply put, describes how
OL,10,Fquickly something heats up or cools
OL,11,Fdown.
OL,13,FThe sea, for example, warms up slowly
OL,14,Fand loses heat slowly (high thermal
OL,15,Finertia), whereas sand, for instance,
OL,16,Fheats up fast on a sunny day and
OL,17,Fquickly cools down after dark (low
OL,18,Fthermal inertia).
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G3/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,309,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30804
